          "body": "The word 'today' stands at the exact center of the psalm's theological argument. It converts the invitation from a general religious sentiment into a specific, unrepeatable present-moment claim. The Spirit's appeal — 'if you would hear His voice' — is conditional, and the condition is hearing. But hearing in the Hebrew sense (shama) always implies obedience; to hear is to heed. The hardened heart is not the heart that has never heard but the heart that has heard and refused. Meribah and Massah were not pagans who had never encountered God — they were the Exodus community, blood-sprinkled, Red-Sea-crossing, manna-eating covenant members who had 'seen My work' (v. 9) and still tested Him. The two Hebrew verbs in verse 9 (nasah, 'tested'; bachan, 'tried') are the verbs used of a prosecutor cross-examining a witness. Israel put God on trial despite having seen His evidence. This is the anatomy of apostasy: familiarity with God's works produces presumption rather than worship, and presumption hardens into defiance."
