          "body": "The psalm's permanent pastoral contribution is the mirror it holds up to corporate worship. Every element of the opening strophe — the shouts, the songs, the thanksgiving, the prostration — can be performed by a congregation whose heart is simultaneously hardening. Hebrews 3:13 provides the diagnostic: 'Encourage one another day after day, as long as it is still called Today, so that none of you will be hardened by the deceitfulness of sin.' The deceitfulness of sin is that it can coexist with external religious practice. The fathers went through the wilderness with the pillar of cloud and fire overhead and still died in unbelief. The congregation of Psalm 95 could enter the temple with instruments playing and voices raised and still be at Meribah. The psalm refuses to let worship be a destination; it insists worship is the doorway through which God's voice speaks — and the response to that voice is the real test. To sing 'Let us come before His presence with thanksgiving' and then ignore His voice is to worship and harden simultaneously. That is the psalm's most searching and most contemporary word."
